I often think that the Millennials may be the last generation who can purely appreciate art and establish a connection with artists. They do not have that pressure, and they do not have to wear a critical, colored lens to examine everything.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, but now, that collective consciousness has disappeared.
Back then, we didn't have to worry about the source of the content, and we could directly immerse ourselves in it, because in those days, tracing back the roots was not an easy task.
We idolized these artists, and we had no reason to question this adoration. Thus, we established a "pseudo-social relationship" with them, and considered it an indispensable part of life.
This also explains why we are so nostalgic.
We used to gather with our friends every Thursday to watch "The Office" while eating pizzas.
This is vastly different from our current experience of watching shows on streaming platforms, where we can watch 12 episodes at once, discuss the plot on social media with warnings about spoilers, or even just communicate with specific groups.
Deep down, we all crave the sense of collective belonging that comes with sharing a common experience.
It's precisely our nostalgia that drives us to rewatch shows like "The Office" and movies like "Air Force One", where iconic lines become memes and are widely shared online.
We quote these iconic lines from the shows and movies, and assume that most people will understand the reference.
Even if something goes viral online, we can no longer assume that everyone has seen it.
With the explosion of information, there's just too much to pay attention to, and we can't even narrow it down…… Can we ever escape this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find out that they're either notorious sex offenders or bigoted extremists, and the cycle repeats itself, becoming tiresome.
We're torn between nostalgia and the harsh reality that the creators of the art we love may have severe moral flaws, leaving us feeling lost and conflicted.
We'll be more cautious in establishing "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realized that if one wants to acquire wealth and power, it's difficult to guarantee that they won't harm or exploit others.
Due to the loss of collective consciousness in the media, we have formed a class consciousness, which helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are also some people who remain oblivious and insist on idolizing others, only to be shocked when the idol falls.
We are in an era of change, and I eagerly want to know where we are heading.
